06823nam a22008175i 9781501760464DE-B159720240306125748.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20212023nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97815017604647 a10.1515/97815017604642doi  a(DE-B1597)582780  a(OCoLC)1240263066  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aHIS0480002bisacsh04a201/.50959809045qOCoLC223/eng/2023112000aReligious Pluralism in Indonesia :bThreats and Opportunities for Democracy /ced. by Chiara Formichi. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2021] 4c©2023  a1 online resource (276 p.) :b3 b&w halftones, 1 map, 1 chart  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aCornell Modern Indonesia Project : 3200tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tAbbreviations -- t1. The L imits of Pancasila as a Framework for Pluralism -- t2. Islamism and the Struggle for Inclusive Citizenship in Democratic Indonesia -- t3. The Rise of Islamist Majoritarianism in Indonesia -- t4. Making the Majority in the Name of Islam: Democratization, Moderate-Radical Coalition, and Religious Intolerance in Indonesia -- t5. Deity Statue Disputed: The Politicization of Religion, Intolerance, and Local Resistance in Tuban, East Java -- t6. The Tragedy of Basuki Tjahaja Purnama -- t7. Regulating Religion and Recognizing “Animist Beliefs” in Indonesian Law and Life -- t8. From Imposed Order to Conflicting Superdiversity: The Tamil Hindu and Their Neighbors in Medan -- t9. Saints, Scholars, and Diplomats: Religious Statecraft and the Problem of “Moderate Islam” in Indonesia -- t10. Agama Hindu under Pressure from Muslim and Christian Proselytizing -- t11. Dispelling Myths of Religious Pluralism: A Critical Look at Maluku and North Maluku -- tGlossary -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn 1945, Sukarno declared that the new Indonesian republic would be grounded on monotheism, while also insisting that the new nation would protect diverse religious practice. The essays in Religious Pluralism in Indonesia explore how the state, civil society groups, and individual Indonesians have experienced the attempted integration of minority and majority religious practices and faiths across the archipelagic state over the more than half century since Pancasila. The chapters in Religious Pluralism in Indonesia offer analyses of contemporary phenomena and events; the changing legal and social status of certain minority groups; inter-faith relations; and the role of Islam in Indonesia's foreign policy. Amidst infringements of human rights, officially recognized minorities—Protestants, Catholics, Hindus, Buddhists and Confucians—have had occasional success advocating for their rights through the Pancasila framework. Others, from Ahmadi and Shi'i groups to atheists and followers of new religious groups, have been left without safeguards, demonstrating the weakness of Indonesia's institutionalized "pluralism."Contributors: Lorraine Aragon, Christopher Duncan, Kikue Hamayotsu, Robert Hefner, James Hoesterey, Sidney Jones, Mona Lohanda, Michele Picard, Evi Sutrisno, Silvia Vignato  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aPancasilavCongresses. 0aReligion and statezIndonesiaxHistoryy20th centuryvCongresses. 0aReligionsxRelationsxHistoryy20th centuryvCongresses. 0aReligious pluralismzIndonesiaxHistoryy20th centuryvCongresses. 0aReligious tolerancezIndonesiaxHistoryy20th centuryvCongresses. 4aIslamic Religion & Studies. 4aReligious Studies. 7aHISTORY / Asia / Southeast Asia.2bisacsh  aReligious Intolerance in Indonesia, Islamism/Fundamentalism, Minority oppression in Indonesia, Islamist majoritarianism, Islam in Indonesia’s foreign policy.1 aAragon, Lorraine V.